<h1>Problem 2131 - 2015 IMOSL, N2, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(a\) and \(b\) be positive integers such that \(a! + b!\) divides \(a!b!\). Prove that \(3a \ge 2b + 2\).</p>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>The really nice idea to size-bound this divisibility is to find a number that
divides the RHS and yet is relatively prime to what we already know divides the
RHS. I’ll call this Nukelid’s Algorithm.</p>
